docs.abstract: Government and industry officials around the world warned of an escalating trade war, but President Trump doubled down on his vow, tweeting, “Trade wars are good, and easy to win.”
docs.snippet: Government and industry officials around the world warned of an escalating trade war, but President Trump doubled down on his vow, tweeting, “Trade wars are good, and easy to win.”
docs.lead_paragraph: BERLIN — The European Union will hit back at the heart of the United States, slapping tariffs on products like Harley-Davidsons, Kentucky bourbon and bluejeans, if President Trump goes ahead with a plan to place tariffs on steel and aluminum imports, the president of the bloc’s executive arm vowed on Friday.

headline.main: E.U. Leader Threatens to Retaliate With Tariffs on Bourbon and Bluejeans

byline.original: By Melissa Eddy and Chad Bray

docs.abstract: The Chinese government’s move to tame an ambitious global deal maker reflects an official willingness to finally curb the country’s addiction to borrowing.
docs.snippet: The Chinese government’s move to tame an ambitious global deal maker reflects an official willingness to finally curb the country’s addiction to borrowing.
docs.lead_paragraph: BEIJING — China’s top leader has a message for his country’s biggest deal makers that could reverberate across the world: Get your debt under control — or else.

headline.main: Anbang Takeover Sends Blunt Message: China Wants to Fix Its Debt Problem
headline.print_headline: With Takeover, China Signals It Will Tame Debt

byline.original: By Keith Bradsher, Alexandra Stevenson and Chris Buckley

docs.abstract: The World Trade Organization found that Europe had improperly subsidized Airbus to the detriment of Boeing. The Trump administration said it could retaliate against imports of European products.
docs.snippet: The World Trade Organization found that Europe had improperly subsidized Airbus to the detriment of Boeing. The Trump administration said it could retaliate against imports of European products.
docs.lead_paragraph: PARIS — The World Trade Organization opened the door for the Trump administration to impose billions of dollars in retaliatory sanctions on European imports with a landmark ruling Tuesday that Europe had illegally subsidized the aircraft giant Airbus to the detriment of its American competitor Boeing.

headline.main: Ruling on Airbus Subsidies Could Escalate Trade Tensions With Europe
headline.print_headline: Airbus Ruling May Escalate E.U. Tensions

docs.abstract: The move by countries in Europe, as well as Australia and Canada, comes against the backdrop of rising support for protectionist practices in the White House.
docs.snippet: The move by countries in Europe, as well as Australia and Canada, comes against the backdrop of rising support for protectionist practices in the White House.
docs.lead_paragraph: PARIS — Europe is pushing for more stringent vetting of foreign investments, with an eye on Beijing. Australia has been blocking bids by Chinese buyers for strategic assets. And in Canada, a Chinese takeover of a major contractor faces a national security test.

headline.main: Wary of China, Europe and Others Push Back on Foreign Takeovers
headline.print_headline: Investment From China Precipitates New Caution

docs.abstract: Ola hopes to become a rare consumer technology firm in India that breaks away from home and grows in a well-to-do market where it can charge more.
docs.snippet: Ola hopes to become a rare consumer technology firm in India that breaks away from home and grows in a well-to-do market where it can charge more.
docs.lead_paragraph: SYDNEY, Australia — Ola built itself into India’s leading ride-hailing company by catering to the particular needs of Indian customers, who often like to settle fares in cash and jump on cheap, three-wheeled auto-rickshaws for short trips.

headline.main: Uber’s New Rival in Australia: An Indian Upstart

byline.original: By Damien Cave and Vindu Goel

docs.abstract: The country reported higher annual growth, but implausibly smooth numbers prompt experts to look for other ways to assess the world’s No. 2 economy.
docs.snippet: The country reported higher annual growth, but implausibly smooth numbers prompt experts to look for other ways to assess the world’s No. 2 economy.
docs.lead_paragraph: HONG KONG — The pace of growth in China’s economy accelerated last year for the first time in seven years as exports, construction and consumer spending all climbed strongly.

headline.main: China’s Economic Growth Looks Strong. Maybe Too Strong.
headline.print_headline: China Reports Strong Economic Growth. The Numbers May Not Add Up.

docs.abstract: Liu He, an influential adviser to President Xi Jinping of China, pledges in a rare public appearance that Beijing will tame its debt within three years.
docs.snippet: Liu He, an influential adviser to President Xi Jinping of China, pledges in a rare public appearance that Beijing will tame its debt within three years.
docs.lead_paragraph: DAVOS, Switzerland — A reclusive and influential senior adviser to President Xi Jinping of China emerged here on Wednesday with a public message that many in the financial world have been eager to hear: The country has a timetable for curbing its vast appetite for debt.

headline.main: China Will Tame Its Growing Debt Load in 3 Years, Top Xi Adviser Says
headline.print_headline: China Plans to Tame Its Debt Within 3 Years, Adviser Says

docs.abstract: The choice of Yi Gang almost guarantees stability in policy as China tries to slow its rise in debt while avoiding any sharp deceleration in economic growth.
docs.snippet: The choice of Yi Gang almost guarantees stability in policy as China tries to slow its rise in debt while avoiding any sharp deceleration in economic growth.
docs.lead_paragraph: China plans to name a new leader for its central bank on Monday in a move signaling that Beijing will continue an ambitious — and, some say, much needed — financial shake-up to get the country’s debt under control and keep its economy growing.

headline.main: China to Name New Central Bank Chief as It Seeks Continuity Amid Change
headline.print_headline: Central Bank In China Set For a Change In Leadership

docs.abstract: Beijing sees its economy as robust enough to defy U.S. tariff threats, potentially leaving Washington with no choice but to escalate or back down.
docs.snippet: Beijing sees its economy as robust enough to defy U.S. tariff threats, potentially leaving Washington with no choice but to escalate or back down.
docs.lead_paragraph: BEIJING — Staking an assertive negotiating stance, China says it will refuse to discuss President Trump’s two toughest trade demands when American officials arrive in Beijing this week, potentially derailing the high-level talks.

headline.main: China Is Set to Take a Hard Line on Trump’s Trade Demands
headline.print_headline: Feeling It Has an Edge, China Sets a Hard Line on U.S. Trade Demands

docs.abstract: President Trump threatened tariffs on $150 billion in goods, then tried conciliation. Beijing’s response either way: Rebuff the offers and avoid specific pledges.
docs.snippet: President Trump threatened tariffs on $150 billion in goods, then tried conciliation. Beijing’s response either way: Rebuff the offers and avoid specific pledges.
docs.lead_paragraph: China has called President Trump’s bluff.

headline.main: Trump’s Charm and Threats May Not Be Working on China. Here’s Why.
headline.print_headline: With Tariffs Postponed, China Takes Victory Lap
